{"file_path":"/project/IMPLEMENTATION_GUIDE.md","content":"# User Action Implementation - Complete Guide

This guide provides complete implementation steps to add User Action functionality to Anki-Android, similar to AnkiMobile.

## Overview

Users can define JavaScript functions (e.g., `revealNext()`) in their card templates and bind keys/gestures to trigger these functions. This is especially useful for:
- Using shared decks with custom keyboard shortcuts
- One-by-one cloze deletion reveals
- Gamepad/controller integration
- Custom gestures for advanced functionality

---

## Implementation Changes

### 1. Modify: AnkiDroid/src/main/java/com/ichi2/anki/cardviewer/ViewerCommand.kt

Add the following enum entries after `RESCHEDULE_NOTE`:

```kotlin
RESCHEDULE_NOTE(R.string.card_editor_reschedule_card),
USER_ACTION_1(R.string.user_action_1),
USER_ACTION_2(R.string.user_action_2),
USER_ACTION_3(R.string.user_action_3),
USER_ACTION_4(R.string.user_action_4),
USER_ACTION_5(R.string.user_action_5),
USER_ACTION_6(R.string.user_action_6),
USER_ACTION_7(R.string.user_action_7),
USER_ACTION_8(R.string.user_action_8),
USER_ACTION_9(R.string.user_action_9);
```

### 2. Modify: AnkiDroid/src/main/assets/scripts/card.js

Add the following functions at the end of the file (after `showAllHints`):

```javascript
/* User actions - allows binding keys/gestures to custom JavaScript functions
 * These functions send signals to AnkiDroid which then executes the user-defined
 * JavaScript in the WebView context.
 */
function triggerUserAction(actionNum) {
    window.location.href = "signal:user_action_" + actionNum;
}

function userAction1() {
    triggerUserAction(1);
}

function userAction2() {
    triggerUserAction(2);
}

function userAction3() {
    triggerUserAction(3);
}

function userAction4() {
    triggerUserAction(4);
}

function userAction5() {
    triggerUserAction(5);
}

function userAction6() {
    triggerUserAction(6);
}

function userAction7() {
    triggerUserAction(7);
}

function userAction8() {
    triggerUserAction(8);
}

function userAction9() {
    triggerUserAction(9);
